indicator.description:
1. Existence of recognized environmental management standards and targets at ILs;
2. Resources used to achieve basic operating standards for environmental management of ILs.
3. IPs and staff competencies and skills in MMA, IBAMA, ICMBio, FUNAI, among others, aligned to implement and follow specific norms and regulations for ethno-management and ethno-zoning in ILs.

target.comment:
Hospital Comunitário de Referência/HCR de Carrefour com pelo menos 50% do total de serviços hospitalares em funcionamento;
Hospital Comunitário de Referência/HCR de Bon Repos com pelo menos 20% do total de serviços hospitalares em funcionamento;
Hospital Comunitário de Referência/HCR de Beudet com pelo menos 20% do total de serviços hospitalares em funcionamento.

actual.comment:
HCR de Carrefour com taxa de implementação de cerca de 75%;
HCR de Bon Repos com taxa de implementação de cerca de 40%
HCR de Beudet com taxa de implementação de cerca de 20%.

indicator.description:
1. Number of signatories;
2. Number of international publications prepared by UNGC Brazil; 
3. Number of CBPG`s members engaged in UN Global Compact Platforms or Sisters Initiatives
4. Numbers of partnerships between UN Agencies and Brazilian Network Companies;

baseline.comment:
No systematic relationship management or communication strategy with current, previous or potential Local Network members;
Absence of structured communication process with Global Compact NY Office, and no participation of the Brazilian network in the GCO decision making process;
New engagement proposition validated in CBPG`s meeting in February 2014. Leadership of Thematic Groups still to be identified;
Signatories companies partnering in a superficial way, without any type of participation from the UNGC Brazil Secretary

target.comment:
Four more cities added to the Global Compact Cities initiative;
Contact at least 40% of the delisted companies;
Reduce the number of delisted companies by 10%
At least two events/per year with the value chain of signatories companies organized; 
10% growth of the network, including additions of some of the biggest and most recognized companies in Brazil;
At least 50% of CBPG members engaged in one one or more GC activity;
At least 4 webinars/per year about the 10 principles organized; 
At least 4 welcome webinars/per year organized; 
Enhancement of 15% of “the advanced COPs status”;
Reduction of 5% of “the COPs learner status”;
100% receipt of CBPG`s members’ contribution.

actual.comment:
4 cities joint the Global Compact;
15% of the delisted companies were contacted. The secretariat had focus on the companies to be delisted;
Increase of 80% of Brazilian delisting signatories – lack of the COP report -, due to the economic crises the sustainability area, especially to SME, didn’t became CORE inside the companies;
7 events promoted to the value chain of Brazilian signatories: 2 public consultations were held (the Food and Agriculture Business Principles, and the Dialogue on Means of Implementation of the Post-2015 Development Agenda); 2 workshops of Anti-corruption; 2 workshops of partnership and 1 annual event; 
The Network has grown 18% in participant members, reaching 657 signatories – 58% business (414) and 42% non-business (243).
55% of CBPG members engaged with the GC activities; 
7 webinars promoted in different issue areas: 3 in training of sustainability report; 2 of engagement and contribution and 2 of Human Rights issue.  
Upgrade in the number of companies reporting with Advanced COPs – from 2% to 16%;
Reduction in the number of companies reporting learner COPs – from 27% to 22;
100% received of CBPG’s member’s contribution;

